  <example>
<p>
    Consider <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(x)-1}{x}}.</m>
    This is a  L<rsq/>HÃ´pital indeterminate so
  <me>
  \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(x)-1}{x}}\lhopeq\frac{\sin(0)}{1}=0.
  </me>
</p>
</example>
<p>
We  want to emphasize very strongly that L<rsq/>HÃ´pital<rsq/>s Rule
requires a L<rsq/>HÃ´pital  indeterminate. If we don<rsq/>t have a L<rsq/>HÃ´pital{
indeterminate we can not use L<rsq/>HÃ´pital<rsq/>s Rule.  If you
try to use L<rsq/>HÃ´pital<rsq/>s Rule when it does not apply, you will
probably not get the correct answer.  The difficulty here is that
nothing in the computations will alert you that anything has gone
wrong. You have to be watchful for this potential pitfall.
</p>

<example>
<p>
  For example, if we mistakenly try to use L<rsq/>HÃ´pital<rsq/>s Rule,
