<p>
Colloquially the phrase <q>exponential growth</q> just means that
something is growing very fast, but it has a more precise meaning in mathematics. It means the growth rate
is described by an exponential function. For example neither
<m>f(x)=x^2</m> nor <m>f(x)=x^{200}</m> grows exponentially. They are both said to  grow <q>polynomially</q>. But <m>f(x) = e^x</m>,
<m>f(x)=2^x</m>, and even <m>f(x)=1.0001^x</m> all do grow exponentially  The
next problem explores how <q>exponential growth</q>  compares
 <q>polynomial growth.</q>
</p>
